and discovers how key elements of the American story—conservation, the New Deal, progressivism, the yeoman myth, and the idea of private property—have collided with and shaped this incomparable landscape. An account of great loss, Rewilding the West also holds out the promise of resurrection—but rather than remake the plains once again, Manning proposes that we now find the wisdom to let the prairies remake us.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrairie restorationzGreat Plains. 4aEnvironmental Conservation & Protection. 4aNature. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aManning, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026795440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094317940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943179423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943179/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles